03954nam a22006015i 9780292798465DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212004txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927984657 a10.7560/7016182doi  a(DE-B1597)588357  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHT653.M6bN877 2004eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.5/2/097209042221 aNutini, Hugo G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Mexican Aristocracy :bAn Expressive Ethnography, 1910–2000 /cHugo G. Nutini. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (398 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 DEMOGRAPHIC COMPOSITION AND CONTEXTUAL DEFINITION OF THE ARISTOCRACY -- tChapter 2 THE RELATIONSHIP OF CLASS AND ETHNICITY -- tChapter 3 THE REALIZATION OF EXPRESSION IN THE ETHNOGRAPHIC CONTEXT -- tChapter 4 THE ORGANIZATION OF URBAN LIVING -- tChapter 5 ECONOMY, MATERIAL CULTURE, AND POLITICAL PARTICIPATION -- tChapter 6 RELIGION -- tChapter 7 SOCIAL ORGANIZATION -- tChapter 8 INTERNAL STRATIFICATION AND ORGANIZATION OF THE GROUP -- tConclusions -- tNotes -- tGlossaries -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Mexican aristocracy today is simultaneously an anachronism and a testimony to the persistence of social institutions. Shut out from political power by the democratization movements of the twentieth century, stripped of the basis of its great wealth by land reforms in the 1930s, the aristocracy nonetheless maintains a strong sense of group identity through the deeply held belief that their ancestors were the architects and rulers of Mexico for nearly four hundred years. This expressive ethnography describes the transformation of the Mexican aristocracy from the onset of the Mexican Revolution of 1910, when the aristocracy was unquestionably Mexico's highest-ranking social class, until the end of the twentieth century, when it had almost ceased to function as a superordinate social group. Drawing on extensive interviews with group members, Nutini maps out the expressive aspects of aristocratic culture in such areas as perceptions of class and race, city and country living, education and professional occupations, political participation, religion, kinship, marriage and divorce, and social ranking. His findings explain why social elites persist even when they have lost their status as ruling and political classes and also illuminate the relationship between the aristocracy and Mexico's new political and economic plutocracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAristocracy (Social class)zMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292798465423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292798465/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK